    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="250"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d250fn1">Sent by the United States Naval Attaché, Moscow,
                        via Navy channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Excerpts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-10">10 October
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Personal and Top Secret for the President from <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                        >Harriman</persName>.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>4. As to the Far East I am a little concerned that the Prime Minister’s talks
                    with <persName corresp="#p_S16">Stalin</persName> may minimize the importance of
                    the conferences that have been agreed to between General <persName
                        corresp="#p_D1">Deane</persName> and the Red Army Staff. We now have a full
                    agreement from <persName corresp="#p_S16">Stalin</persName> not only to
                    participate in the Pacific war but to enter the war with full effort. The
                    important thing now therefore is to ascertain what are the Russians’
                    capabilities in the East. In this the limiting factors are of course the <pb
                        facs="0449" n="363" xml:id="pg_363"/> logistics about which we know so
                    little. General talks are no longer needed and full discussions by General
                        <persName corresp="#p_D1">Deane</persName> are therefore the next essential
                    step. The Prime Minister’s talks therefore with <persName corresp="#p_S16"
                        >Stalin</persName> should emphasize the importance of the detailed Staff
                    discussions. I will try to see that the Prime Minister’s conversations take this
                    line. I have already General Ismay’s agreement.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>It would be helpful to have your reaction to any of the above for my
                    guidance.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
